properties.Title: High Water Advisory Alert Issued For The Interlake
properties.Summary:
Description: This is a Manitoba Emergency Alert. Manitoba Infrastructure's Hydrologic Forecast Centre has issued a High Water Advisory for parts of the Interlake region due to expected high flows. If you are in the affected area, be watchful of local waterways as flooding is likely to occur. Do not attempt to cross fast flowing waters or waters of unknown depth. Avoid flooded areas. Follow all directions by the local authorities. Listen for updates and take all necessary precautions to stay safe. Up to date information is available at www.gov.mb.ca/flooding and www.manitoba511.ca or stay tuned to local media.
Expires: 2019-10-18T14:30:00-05:00

Area: Interlake region of Manitoba

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Significant prolonged rainfall is expected. Total rainfall: 60 to 100 mm. Locations: From Natuashish to Hopedale. Timespan: Beginning near noon Friday and tapering off to showers Sunday afternoon. Remarks: Rainfall amounts could exceed warning criteria of 75 mm in 48 hours. It is also likely that some snow will accumulate over the highest elevations of the inland terrain. Anyone using mountain trails should be prepared for winter weather. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.
Expires: 2019-10-18T16:30:14-00:00

properties.Title: Storm Surge Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Higher than normal water levels are expected near the shore this evening. Warning of potential coastal flood conditions issued jointly by Fisheries and Oceans Canada (science) and the Meteorological Service of Canada - Quebec area, on 2019-10-17. An intense low pressure system moving up the American Eastern Seaboard is giving strong to high winds over the area mentioned below. The combination of these winds and the fact that we are currently in a period of medium tidal ranges could produce coastal flooding in the vicinity of the following locality at the dates and times (Eastern Daylight Time). Quebec City: 2019-10-17, from 8 PM to 10:30 PM. ### Coastal flooding is possible along the shoreline. Coastal erosion is possible in vulnerable areas. Storm surge warnings are issued when water levels pose a threat to coastal regions. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to QCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #QCStorm.
Expires: 2019-10-18T07:39:10-00:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Environment Canada, 2019-10-17T23:20:10-00:00, urn:oid:2.49.0.1.124.2122644451.2019
Area: Québec area, Côte-de-Beaupré - L'Île d'Orléans area, Bellechasse area, Lévis area
properties.Author: Environment Canada

properties.Summary:
Description: Significant rainfall is expected. Total rainfall: 30 to 45 mm. Locations: eastern and southern Avalon Peninsula. Timespan: tonight until Friday evening. The rain is expected to taper off over all areas by Friday night. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. properties.Title: High Water Level Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Higher than normal water levels are expected or occurring. An intense low pressure system tracking toward the region will give severe easterly winds. These winds will produce waves which in combination with a storm surge will give higher than normal waters at high tide this evening. These water levels will result in flooding along coastlines and potential erosion to beaches and damage to infrastructure. ### Coastal flooding is likely, especially during high tide. Coastal erosion is possible in vulnerable areas. High water level warnings are issued when water levels pose a threat to coastal regions. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. For more information monitor Canadian Coast Guard radio or Weatheradio stations.
Expires: 2019-10-18T04:04:25-00:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Environment Canada, 2019-10-17T22:44:25-00:00, urn:oid:2.49.0.1.124.1655022901.2019
Area: Anticosti, Chaleur - Miscou
properties.Author: Environment Canada

properties.Title: Blizzard Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Blizzard conditions with gusty winds and visibility frequently near zero in snow and blowing snow are expected or occurring. An area of high pressure situated over the Arctic Ocean and an intense low pressure system over the Gulf of Alaska will continue to produce conditions favourable for strong, gusty winds near the Richardson Mountains. The strong winds, falling snow and existing snow pack will combine to produce blizzard conditions through at least Friday. ### Travel is expected to be extremely hazardous due to reduced visibility. Blizzard warnings are issued when widespread reduced visibilities of 400 metres or less are expected for at least 4 hours. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather in British Columbia or Yukon, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or YTstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm or #YTStorm.
Expires: 2019-10-18T15:48:19-00:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Environment Canada, 2019-10-17T23:49:19-00:00, urn:oid:2.49.0.1.124.4103624276.2019
Area: Dempster

properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snowfall with total amounts of 10 to 15 cm is expected. A disturbance tracking northeastward out of the Northwest Territories spread snow into Baker Lake this afternoon which will continue tonight. The snow should taper off to light on Friday morning. Total accumulations of 10 to 15 cm are expected along with southeast winds gusting to 70 km/h and blowing snow at times. Another disturbance will spread more snow into the area Friday afternoon but this should become mixed with rain Friday evening which will limit snowfall amounts with the next system. ### Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NUstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NUStorm.
Expires: 2019-10-18T12:29:55-00:00

Area: Baker Lake
